|}

There were 144 passengers and six crew members on board, most of them German and Spanish nationals<ref name="BBC live"/> but from at least 18 nations in total. The count may be confused due to [[dual citizenship]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2015/03/germanwings_flight_9525_crash.html|title=Germanwings Flight 9525 crash: 2 Americans among 150 killed|accessdate=25 March 2015|publisher=AL.com|date=25 March 2015}}</ref> Amongst them were 16 schoolchildren and two teachers from the [[Joseph-König-Gymnasium]] of [[Haltern|Haltern am See]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]. They were on their way home from a student exchange with the Giola Institute in [[Llinars del Vallès]], [[province of Barcelona|Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/germanwings-a320-crash-victims-include-15-german-schoolchildren-local-media-reports-1857200|title=Germanwings A320 Crash Victims Include 15 German Schoolchildren, Local Media Reports|date=24 March 2015|work=International Business Times|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> Haltern's mayor, {{link-interwiki|en=Bodo Klimpel|lang=de}}, has described it as "the darkest day in the history of our city."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.yahoo.com/16-school-children--2-teachers-believed-to-be-aboard-germanwings-flight-4u9525-150823821.html|title=16 schoolchildren believed to be aboard Germanwings plane that crashed in Alps|date=24 March 2015|work=Yahoo News|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref>

Germanwings has not disclosed the identities of the pilots, but has announced that the captain had 10 years of flying experience (6000 flight hours)<ref name="avherald">{{cite web|title=Crash: Germanwings A320 near Barcelonnette on Mar 24th 2015, lost height and impacted terrain|url=http://avherald.com/h?article=483a5651|publisher=The Aviation Herald|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> with Germanwings and [[Lufthansa]] flying A320s.<ref name="bbc-whatweknow">{{cite web|title=Alps plane crash: What we know |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-32035121|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref>

The [[Deutsche Oper am Rhein]] confirmed that [[bass-baritone]] [[Oleg Bryzhak]] was among the passengers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://operamrhein.de/|title=Oleg Bryjak unter den Opfern des Airbus-Absturzes|trans_title=Oleg Bryjak among the victims of the Airbus crash|date=24 March 2015|work=Deutsche Oper am Rhein|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> as was German [[contralto]] [[Maria Radner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/germanwings-airbus-a320-plane-crash-5394028|title=Germanwings Airbus A320 plane crash: First pictures of opera singers Maria Radner and Oleg Bryjak among 150 dead|author=John Shammas|date=24 March 2015|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|accessdate=24 March 2015|location=[[London]]}}</ref> Members of the [[Swedish Football Division 1|Swedish football]] team [[Dalkurd FF]] were booked to be on the flight but changed at the last moment.<ref name="AusBC"/>

==Investigation==
The French national civil aviation enquiries bureau, ''[[Bureau d'Enquêtes et d'Analyses pour la Sécurité de l'Aviation Civile]]'' (BEA), has opened an investigation into the crash, joined by its German counterpart, the [[German Federal Bureau of Aircraft Accidents Investigation|Federal Bureau of Aircraft Accidents Investigation]] (BFU). On 24 March, the BEA sent seven investigators to the crash site, accompanied by representatives from [[Airbus]] and [[CFM International]]. The BEA will hold a press conference on 25 March from 16:00 to 16:45 UTC.<ref>{{cite web|title= Accident to the Airbus A320-211 registered D-AIPX, flight GWI18G, on 24 March 2015|url=http://www.bea.aero/en/enquetes/flight.gwi18g/flight.gwi18g.php|publisher=Bureau d'Enquêtes et d'Analyses pour la Sécurité de l'Aviation Civile|accessdate=24 March 2015|language=French|date=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aviationtribune.com/safety/item/2156-germanwings-flight-4u9525-crashes-in-french-alps |accessdate=25 March 2015 |date=24 March 2015 |title=Germanwings flight 4U9525 crashes in French Alps (updated) |work=Aviation Tribune}}</ref>

The [[cockpit voice recorder]] (CVR) was recovered by rescue workers and is being examined by the investigation team.<ref name="rt.c_Germ">{{Cite web| title = Germanwings A320 black box found in French Alps| author = | publisher = [[RT (TV network)|RT]]| date = 24 March 2015| accessdate = 24 March 2015| url = http://rt.com/news/243669-germanwings-flight-recorder-found/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Germanwings plane black box found as investigators reach crash site |work=theguardian.com |url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/mar/24/germanwings-plane-black-box-found-as-investigators-reach-crash-site |date=24 March 2015 |accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> The recorder was damaged in the crash, but was said to be still in a "usable" condition.<ref name="foxnews.com"/> The BEA released photos of the CVR<ref name=BEA>{{cite web |url=http://www.bea.aero/fr/enquetes/vol.gwi18g/mediatheque.php |title=BEA France releases photos of Cockpit Voice Recorder |accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref> and was able to extract a voice recording.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/25/us-france-crash-investigation-idUSKBN0ML1Y320150325 |title=Useable voice recording recovered from Alps crash: investigators |date=25 March 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2015 |publisher=Reuters |author=Tim Hepher |location=Paris}}</ref>

The outer casing of the missing [[flight data recorder]] was found the next day, but was severely damaged and missing its memory module.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/germanwings-flight-4u9525-search-back-on-for-flight-data-recorder-1.3008432 |accessdate=25 March 2015 |date=25 March 2015 |title=Germanwings Flight 4U9525: Search back on for flight data recorder |work=CBC.ca}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/1.12280269 |accessdate=25 March 2015 |date=25 March 2015 |title=NRK news |work=NRK.no}}</ref> The BEA press conference on 25 March confirmed the times, route and altitude, during the final descent of the aircraft, previously given by Flightradar24.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/flightradar24/status/580764636494086145|title= BEA press conference confirms Flightradar24|accessdate=25 March 2015}}{{Unreliable source?|date=March 2015}}</ref>{{Citation needed|reason=Where are BEA 25 March 2015 press conference slides?|date=March 2015}}

French [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Interior Minister]] [[Bernard Cazeneuve]] announced{{when|date=March 2015}} that terrorism was not a likely “hypothesis at the moment”.{{cn|date=March 2015}}

On 25 March, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported from a source on the investigation team that the cockpit voice recording revealed that one of the pilots had been locked out of the cockpit and had been trying to break down the door. He started by knocking lightly and then, getting no response, began hitting the door harder. He also reportedly tried to break the door down, to no avail.<ref name=Clark/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/25/europe/germanwings-crash-main/index.html|title=Germanwings crash report: Pilot locked out of cockpit - CNN.com|author=Josh Levs and Catherine E. Shoichet, CNN|date=25 March 2015|work=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/27/world/europe/germanwings-crash.html|title=Revelations About Pilot Add to Mystery of Germanwings Crash|last=Clark|first=Nicola|coauthors=Dan Bilefsky|work=The New York Times|accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref> This report was not confirmed by official sources.

==Response==
<!-- Please see [[WP:OVERQUOTE]] before adding any condolence quotes to this section! -->
French Minister of the Interior Bernard Cazeneuve remarked that due to the "violence of the impact" there was "little hope" that any survivors would be found.<ref name="National Post">{{cite news |title=‘The plane is disintegrated': 150 dead as Airbus A320 goes down in Southern France |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2015/03/24/survivors-unlikely-after-airbus-carrying-148-passengers-crashes-in-southern-france/ |newspaper=[[National Post]] |location=[[Toronto]], Canada |date=24 March 2015 |accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Manuel Valls]] said he had dispatched Interior Minister Cazeneuve to the scene and set-up a ministerial crisis cell to co-ordinate the response to the incident.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|title=Germanwings airliner crashes in French Alps|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-32030270|accessdate=24 March 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=24 March 2015}}</ref>

[[Monarchy of Spain|King]] [[Felipe VI of Spain|Philip VI]] of Spain, in Paris for a [[state visit]] to France at the time of the crash, announced his decision to cut his visit short and return to Spain.<ref name="BBC live"/>

German [[Chancellor of Germany|Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]] announced that she would travel to the crash site on 25 March together with [[Minister-President#Germany|Minister-President]] of [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] [[Hannelore Kraft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2015-03-24/angela-merkel-to-travel-to-germanwings-crash-site/ |title=Angela Merkel to travel to Germanwings crash site |publisher=ITV News |date=24 March 2015 |accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="edit_Fren">{{Cite web| title = France crash: Germanwings plane obliterated, data recorder found| last = Botelho | first = Greg| last2 = Smith-Spark | first2 = Laura| last3 = Hanna | first3 = Jason| publisher = [[CNN]]| date = 24 March 2015| accessdate = 24 March 2015| url = http://edition.cnn.com/2015/03/24/europe/france-plane-crash/index.html}}</ref> Foreign Minister [[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]] flew over the crash site on 24 March, describing it as "a picture of horror".<ref name=BBC />

Merkel, French Prime Minister Valls, and Spanish [[Prime Minister of Spain|Prime Minister]] [[Mariano Rajoy]] visited the recovery operations base at [[Seyne|Seyne-les-Alpes]] on 25 March.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.english.rfi.fr/europe/20150325-hollande-merkel-rajoy-visit-germanwings-a320-crash-site-barcelona-dusseldorf |title=Hollande, Merkel, Rajoy visit Germanwings A320 crash site |publisher=[[Radio France Internationale|RFI]] |date=25 March 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>

Lufthansa Chief Executive [[Carsten Spohr]] visited the crash location on 25 March and afterwards said that this is "the darkest day for Lufthansa in its 60-year history".<ref name="ITVlufthansa25mar">{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2015-03-25/lufthansa-boss-says-past-hours-darkest-in-60-year-history/ |title=Lufthansa boss says past hours 'darkest in 60-year history' |publisher=ITV News |date=25 March 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>

Germanwings reported occasional flight disruptions on 24–25 March within its route network due to crew members deciding not to operate aircraft following the accident. As a result some flights had to be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.germanwings.com/en/information/current-information.html|title=Current information - Information - Germanwings|work=germanwings.com|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>

On 25 March, Germanwings retired the flight number 4U9525, changing it to 4U9441. The outbound flight number was also changed, from 4U9524 to 4U9440. The flight numbers for the later Düsseldorf to Barcelona flight were unchanged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://airlineroute.net/2015/03/24/4u-mar15/|title=germanwings Retires Flight Number 4U9525; New Flight Numbers from 25MAR15|work=airlineroute.net|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref>

